## The Band Gap

The Band Gap is the geometric problem that cushion cut engagement ring owners discover after purchase — and that almost no jeweller explains before the sale.

Here is exactly what happens. A cushion cut engagement ring sits on the finger with a setting head that is wider than the band shank. That head — the prong basket or halo that holds the center stone — extends above and slightly outward from the band's profile. When you place a second straight band next to the engagement ring, the straight band's profile curves away from the setting head at the junction point. On a round brilliant solitaire, the curve is predictable and the gap is minimal because the setting head is also round. On a cushion solitaire or halo, the setting head is four-sided, and the gap that forms at each side of the head is rectangular — an obvious visual break that reads as a sizing or pairing error.

[![Cushion cut diamond seven-stone band in white gold stacked lifestyle shot](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/LifeStyleV4/DiamondBasics/603263/603263_CSH_0125CT_W_2_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings?stoneShape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Why cushion is more affected than other shapes.** The Band Gap exists for all engagement ring shapes to some degree, but it is most visible with cushion for two reasons. First, the cushion modified brilliant's squared-off corner geometry creates a harder visual break between the setting head and the band than the softer transitions of oval or round. Second, the cushion's typical head width (the distance across the setting at its widest point) is greater than for equivalent round brilliants — more head surface for the gap to appear against.

**Three ways to solve The Band Gap:**

1. **Cushion-shaped band stones** — a band with cushion cut melee diamonds follows the same aesthetic as the center stone. When the shapes match, the slight gap at the junction reads as intentional negative space rather than a fit error. Seven-stone cushion bands solve The Band Gap visually without requiring a custom curved profile.

2. **Full eternity band** — a band with diamonds all the way around creates a continuous diamond border that frames the engagement ring from every angle. There is no straight-section gap visible because the diamonds wrap continuously. Full eternity cushion bands are the most visually impressive solution.

3. **Curved/contour band** — a custom-fabricated band with a notch or curve built to wrap around the specific engagement ring's setting profile. This eliminates The Band Gap physically but requires custom fabrication and exact measurements from the engagement ring manufacturer. Blue Nile does not currently offer contour cushion bands in their standard collection; this is a custom jeweller solution.

